// Lamport clocks give us a partial order of events.
// But they can't tell us if two events are concurrent.
//
// Vector clocks solve this: each process keeps a vector
// of counters — one per process in the system.
//
// If V(a) < V(b) then a happened-before b.
// If neither V(a) < V(b) nor V(b) < V(a) → concurrent.
//
// This is the foundation of conflict detection in
// distributed databases like DynamoDB and Riak.

// If e=3 and the same message m is sent to 3 recipients
// each with different moduli n1, n2, n3:
//
// c1 = m^3 mod n1
// c2 = m^3 mod n2
// c3 = m^3 mod n3
//
// By CRT we recover m^3 mod (n1*n2*n3)
// Since m < ni for all i, m^3 < n1*n2*n3
// So we just compute the integer cube root.
//
// Fix: always use OAEP padding.
